The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 24, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, May 23: The Reserve Bank of Indias working group on small and medium enterprises (SMEs) has recommended that banks should promote finance companies, which will not accept deposits from public, to extend quick credit to the SME sector. There is a need for financial intermediaries aimed at financing small units, the report said. NBFCs would draw their resources from the banking system, by originating the loans and selling the same to the banks as a portfolio with appropriate arrangements for risk sharing, the report said.																								 New Delhi, May 23: Power Trading Corporation (PTC) is setting up the first power exchange in the country for which the company is likely to rope in an international partner. The company is setting up a platform that would ultimately enable efficient bidding, pricing, scheduling and settlement of transaction in electricity on a real-time basis, PTC sources said.																								 Singapore, May 23: Videsh Sanchar Nigam Ltd (VSNL) will launch virtual calling cards in Singapore for the Indian diaspora and tourists visiting this country to enable them to call back home.																								 Singapore, May 23: Rolta India Ltd plans to set up a subsidiary in Singapore, which is expected to be operational by June 30, to tap over 7,000 multinational companies stationed in the country and extend its reach to Southeast Asian markets.																								 Bangalore, May 23: Infosys Technologies Ltd is concerned that regulatory barriers could stall moving work offshore, even though it said the clamour against outsourcing by American firms to Indian IT companies has come down.
